,Not Recommended,318570,33638259,Posted: 18 July,all,Verdantil,"Tags: Tower DefenseAdditional Tags: Tactical - FantasyDelete Local Content & Remove from LibraryTLDR: Unity engine clicker board game hybrid with strange difficulty spikes, odd goal placement mechanics, slippery slope and ressource management risk/reward management and understocked in the diversity of visual and audio assets to fully immerse. The moody ambiant track was actually memorable and made the game worthy of returning to in small doses. Feels distantly like a primitive underachieved tablet version of Darkest DungeonsA board style game with tower defense combat. Good atmosphere and core concept but dev did not fully realize in execution leaving a grindy repetitive clumsy and rather unbalanced experience to deal with.Great game but feels like an alpha. Game tells you to follow clues of Van Helsing to find Dracula but I played this for over 5 hours and I never saw any such thing. From what I can tell Dracula, which is the main goal, can spawn at any time in early zones or in advanced zones and there is no rhyme or reason to it. End boss battle not well thought out, game has you grind all abilities to max to start out with a decent chance at being able to play and not die immediately.Every tile that is 1 hex away from start location is zone 1 - 2 hexes are zone 2 and difficulty scales up rapidly. Each hex can be one of nine districts which improve an aspect of your faction every turn, for example being able to heal quicker for the hospitals. User interface is a little on the clunky side.Rapid movement on the combat map is difficult, the action points based system is hard to balance with health management. The inability to go to the next turn without having to explore is disappointing especially mid game when you need to recover and are forced to go several zones in just to uncover a square and make the days pass, exposing you to very real risks of a game over encounter.The end goal is to kill Dracula which is an overpowered unique monster that sometimes telegraphs that he is in the fight by taunting you and then showing up as a random spawn. He teleports around, can tank way too much damage and moves through the battlefield way too fast. With no way to pin him down it would take nothing short of a massive grinded army of guys to take him down.Because yeah, this is plants vs zombies, but instead of just having a card u spend coins on to spawn towers, you get ONE tower when you uncover a house tile, which you can customize with a weapon from the gun shop tile, and thats it, you gotta babysit this tower because when it dies it is gone forever. So achievement this level of grind would be no small feat, and after all the grind necessary to even get this game started thats a daunting prospect. Because yeah, the game starts you off in a tower defense with one tower, most basic weapon, and then spawns foes on all lanes.You cant win, and have to grind to have a starting deck that can even remotely put up some kind of a defense. Even then there are a lot of spinning plates all at once and you will mess up sooner or later. I think if this game had been retweaked it could had been really good but it has been released a long time ago and I am not expecting the gameplay to fundamentally change."
,Not Recommended,318570,13964609,"Posted: 12 January, 2015",all,anrkyuk,"When I first watched a gameplay video for this game it reminded me of the excellent ""Rebuild"" flash browser game and looked similar in many ways with the added bonus of tactical combat ....... oh how wrong I was.This game is nothing but a pointless and mindnumbing grind.You start the game with one guy with a pistol and a base. you have to explore buildings to find additional people ( hunters ), weapons, base defence upgrades and resources. Each hunter only has a linited number of action points before they have to be rested and made inactive, they can also be replenished if you find resources to do so. while this is a nice idea in principle you can not skip a turn as such when a hunter is rested for AP or in hospital you still have to explore and each time you explore there is a risk of an encounter and if theres no active hunter or you lack AP then your base gets♥♥♥♥♥♥♥On principle all this sounds ok and it is ... sort of. as you play you earn points, these points can be used during battles to heal your hunters, kill all mobs on screen, as an xp boost etc, however these points are also the some points that are used to buy upgrades on the main menu that carry over all future games, such as starting with more hunters, increased starting level of hunters, better and more starting guns, strong base defences etc.Now heres the key gripe, the game is impossible to beat without significant investment in these upgrades, you simply grind the game to get the points to purchase all the upgrades from the main menu and then once done you play your final playthrough and complete the game.There are no high score tables, no achievements to earn and as such little point in playing the game beyond earning trading cards.As stated by others this feels very much like a freemium mobile game and I'm such it would have been a reasonable concept for it however asking £3.99 for this game when there are alternatives like Rebuild and Rebuild 2 available to play for free on the web paying for this game just does not make any sense.There is no story, and no challange or reward for wanting to play this game any further, each time you play you'll earn points towards and upgrade and with each upgrade you will last that bit longer untill you have purchased enough upgrades to last long enough to complete the game and then thats it, the end.Dev Feedback -Add a high score tableMake it so that hunters can move to anywhere on the board with one move not just one square up/down/left/rightSeperate points used for ingame battle bonuses and menu upgrades***EDIT***Well after a few more hours of playthrough I am about to ""complete"" the game having obtained all upgrades and it's fair to say it has even more issues. The UI is too big and you can not zoom out far enough, once you explore 4 or 5 buildings away from your base buildings appear obstructed by the UI and even off the screen and are in accessable, it is entirely possible to break the game by running out of buildings to expore on screen if you do not kill the boss before doing so. Either needs a higher res which is not adjustable in game or ability to zoom out further.***EDIT#2***Having just completed the game and a little late to find out you can move the screen around holding LMB down and moving mouse, something that could have perhaps been mentioned somewhere as it is kind of important."
